actices of literate, illiterate, and semi-literate Egyptians alike. Students who wrote petitions, women who frequented scribes, and communities who gathered to hear a newspaper read aloud all used various literacies to participate in social exchanges and civic negotiations regarding the most important issues of their day. Composing Egypt illustrates how reading and writing practices became not only an object of social reform, but also a central medium for public exchange. Wide segments of society could engage with new ideas about nationalism, education, gender, and, ultimately, what it meant to be part of "modern Egypt."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBooks and readingzEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aBooks and readingzEgyptxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiteracyxSocial aspectszEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiteracyxSocial aspectszEgyptxHistoryy20th century. 4aArabic. 4aeducation. 4agender. 4ailliteracy. 4aliteracies. 4aliteracy. 4aprotests. 4apublic literacies. 4apublic sphere. 4areading and writing. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804799218zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799218423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799218.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles